<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870306-0129 </DOCNO><HL> Letters to the Editor:GM Needed Perot</HL><DD> 03/06/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> GMAUTOS, AUTO PARTS (AUT) </IN><TEXT>   From your Feb. 6 article &quot;GM Net Fell . . . ,&quot; GM appears to be in trouble. Its top-line sedans and expensive coupes look alike. The Saturn project seems to have lost momentum. It feels as if GM has forsaken the client for issues of the bottom line. You state that Roger Smith &quot;. . . has launched an ambitious public-relations campaign to quell the chorus of criticism. . . .&quot; Presumably Mr. Smith is being criticized for his handling of H. Ross Perot's departure. Mr. Smith should have corralled Mr. Perot's spirit and channeled it to the good of GM. Stemming criticism is less important than correcting what caused it.    People like Ross Perot are aggressive entrepreneurs who win at free enterprise by making things happen. Mr. Perot was just the medicine that GM needed. GM rejected him. Worse yet, it paid him to leave!    Those who oppose individuals like Mr. Perot are content with the status quo. They love the bureaucratic morass that gives them comfort and equilibrium.    Paul D. Renselle   President   Software Consulting Specialists Inc.   Fort Wayne, Ind.</TEXT></DOC>